#week-title("Three", "The Seasonal Rhythm of the Laboratory")

=== Core Teaching

The living laboratory has a seasonal character. This is not merely a matter of
temperature (though ambient temperature affects preparations significantly) —
it is the expression of the cosmic seasonal cycle, governed by the Sun's
transit through the zodiac and the corresponding shifts in the World Spirit's
expression in the natural world.

*The four seasonal thresholds.* The solstices and equinoxes mark the four great
alchemical seasons of the year:

- *Spring Equinox (Sun enters Aries):* The season of beginnings; the appropriate
  time for beginning new extractions, new macerations, new circulations. The
  World Spirit is ascending; the volatile is in ascent.
- *Summer Solstice (Sun enters Cancer):* The season of maximum solar force; the
  appropriate time for solar and gold-related work; for the highest-temperature
  operations of the year. Some traditions regard the period around the summer
  solstice as particularly powerful for long circulations already underway.
- *Autumn Equinox (Sun enters Libra):* The season of review and balance; the
  appropriate time for assessing the state of all active preparations, reviewing
  the long-work logs, and deciding what to carry forward and what to conclude.
- *Winter Solstice (Sun enters Capricorn):* The season of depth and fixation;
  Saturn's domain; the appropriate time for slow, cold digestions and for the
  most patient, most fixed aspects of the mineral work.

*Temperature considerations.* In most climates, the laboratory's ambient
temperature varies significantly across the year. This affects preparations
without external heating — a preparation digesting on a warm shelf in summer
may be cooler than desired in winter. The practitioner attends to this: some
preparations may require supplementary heating in the cold months that they
did not need in summer.

*The practitioner's seasonal rhythm.* The practitioner's own energy and
attention also have seasonal character. The inner work that comes most naturally
in winter (long, inward, patient descent) differs from what comes most naturally
in spring (beginning, opening, the excitement of new growth). Observing this
personal seasonal rhythm without fighting it — working with it rather than
against it — is part of the long-term intelligence of the practice.

=== Topics This Week

- The four alchemical seasons: Spring, Summer, Autumn, Winter as operative framework
- Temperature management across seasons for active preparations
- The practitioner's own seasonal rhythm and how to work with it
- Planning the remaining months of Year Three within the seasonal framework

